The article discusses a joint statement on transport security made by participating countries at the Nuclear Security Summit in Seoul. The participants reaffirm their commitment to enhancing the security of nuclear and radioactive materials during domestic and international transport. They encourage states to share best practices and cooperate in acquiring necessary technologies. The statement emphasizes the importance of establishing effective national nuclear material inventory management and domestic tracking mechanisms to prevent the loss or theft of materials. The participating countries also express their commitment to holding working group meetings, organizing training exercises, and submitting proposals to strengthen transport security. Security-related officials from organizations such as the IMO, ICAO, and IAEA will be invited for discussions.